== 3. Bf4 ==

White is playing the London system, where they plan to support d4 with their e3 pawn and eventually plant their knight on e5, controlled by the e pawn and the dark square bishop. Now that they have developed their bishop, they can play e3 without trapping it behind the pawn chain. 

The London system is a system opening, where White has the same general ideas to many Black responses and the specific orders are very flexible. This position can also arise from the [[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...Nf6/2. Bf4/2...d5|Accelerated London 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6]] where 3. Nf3 transposes.

Black has several approaches to the position, including ...c5 and ...Qb6 to pressure White's b2 pawn, weakened by moving the bishop away.

